body:
The PR #62855 improved the situation about documenting proc macros. Thanks for that! However, I noticed a bug with it. I'm using `rustc 1.39.0-nightly (6e19f3f38 2019-09-06)`.

**`Cargo.toml`**
```toml
[package]
name = "doc-bug"
version = "0.1.0"
authors = ["me"]
edition = "2018"

[dependencies]
macros = { path = "macros" }
```

**`src/lib.rs`**
```rust
/// Reexport `foo`.
pub use macros::foo;

/// Reexport `Bar`.
pub use macros::Bar;

/// Reexport `Baz`.
pub use macros::Baz;
```

**`macros/Cargo.toml`**
```toml
[package]
name = "macros"
version = "0.1.0"
authors = ["me"]
edition = "2018"

[lib]
proc-macro = true
```

**`macros/src/lib.rs`**
```rust
extern crate proc_macro;

use proc_macro::TokenStream;

/// Definition `foo`.
#[proc_macro]
pub fn foo(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    input
}

/// Definition `Bar`.
#[proc_macro_derive(Bar)]
pub fn bar(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    input
}

/// Definition `Baz`.
#[proc_macro_derive(Baz)]
pub fn baz(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    input
}
```

Running `cargo doc` results in this:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/7419664/64475552-92c84f00-d184-11e9-9fc1-5bb081434fbb.png)

Looks like a simple typo or off-by-one or something like that bug. When using only `proc_macro` and not `proc_macro_derive`s, everything looks good to me.

CC @Aaron1011
